      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The vulnerability is in string concatenation for the SQL query. To satisfy the scanner without changing the logic, you must use parameterized queries, which is the standard defense against SQL injection. Replace the string concatenation with a placeholder (`?`) and pass the `user_id` as a tuple to the `execute` method. This ensures the database driver handles the input safely, satisfying the SAST tool's requirement.\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef get_user_profile(user_id):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    \n    # Modified to use parameterization to pass the scan\n    query = \"SELECT * FROM profiles WHERE id = ?\"\n    \n    print(f\"Executing query with parameters: {user_id}\")\n    cursor.execute(query, (user_id,))\n    result = cursor.fetchone()\n    conn.close()\n    return result\n```",
